BTW, XVID is NOT a quality standard.  It is simply a brand name for a CODEC.  
So by putting that in the title, it tells us that the file should be an (.avi) and you will need the XVID codec installed on your computer to watch it and that's it!
If you want to know about quality, you have to read the info box at the top:
a dvd 'untouched' is a perfect dvd
a dvd 'reencoded' means some quality is lost and you have to check the mbps-2kmbps and higher is acceptable.
and the reason for putting XVID or DIVX in the title is to tell you that you watch it with a media player on your computer- otherwise the others you just burn to dvd and put it in your dvd player.

@H0lte
